---
import ToolLayout from '../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';
import LumensToWattsCalculator from '../components/calculators/LumensToWattsCalculator';
import FaqBlock from '../components/FaqBlock.astro';
import RelatedTools from '../components/RelatedTools.astro';
import AdSlot from '../components/AdSlot.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import { lumensToWattsFaqs } from '../data/faqs';
import { ledEfficiencyPresets } from '../data/lightingPresets';

const path = '/lumens-to-watts-calculator';
---

<ToolLayout
  title="Lumens to Watts Calculator for LED Lighting"
  description="Convert total lumens to estimated LED wattage using fixture efficiency. Plan office and workspace lighting power requirements before you buy fixtures."
  path={path}
  h1="Lumens to Watts Calculator"
  subtitle="Estimate LED wattage from total lumens and fixture efficacy — useful for electrical planning and energy budgeting."
  faqSchema={lumensToWattsFaqs}
>
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-main mb-6">Calculator</h2>
    <LumensToWattsCalculator client:load />
  </section>

  <AdSlot />

  <section class="prose-content">
    <h2>How this calculator works</h2>
    <p>
      LED lighting shifted how we think about brightness. With incandescent bulbs, people often used
      watts as a proxy for brightness — a “60 W equivalent” label still appears on packaging. For
      modern workspace design, watts measure electrical power consumption, not how much useful light
      reaches your desk. <strong>Lumens</strong> describe output; <strong>watts</strong> describe
      draw. The link between them is efficacy: lumens per watt (lm/W).
    </p>
    <p>
      The formula is straightforward: <strong>watts = lumens ÷ lm/W</strong>. Ten thousand lumens at
      100 lm/W equals about 100 watts of LED lighting. The same 10,000 lumens at 150 lm/W high-efficiency
      fixtures needs only about 67 watts. Efficacy varies by chip quality, driver losses, thermal design,
      and whether rated lumens are delivered at full power or after aging. Always check the manufacturer
      datasheet for rated lumens and wattage at the same operating conditions.
    </p>
    <p>
      This calculator is most useful after you know total lumens — from our
      <a href="/lux-to-lumens-calculator">Lux to Lumens Calculator</a> or
      <a href="/office-lighting-calculator">Office Lighting Calculator</a>. Enter that total and select
      an efficiency preset: 80 lm/W for basic LED, 100 lm/W standard, 120 lm/W efficient, or 150 lm/W
      premium. The result estimates aggregate fixture wattage, not necessarily one circuit breaker load
      if fixtures are distributed across phases and zones.
    </p>
    <p>
      Do not rely on “100 W incandescent = X LED watts” comparisons for office layouts. Incandescent
      comparisons ignore lux targets, room size, and distribution. Plan from lux → lumens → watts in
      that order. Dimming reduces power draw below rated wattage when lights are not at full output —
      energy models for smart buildings should use actual dimming profiles, not nameplate maxima alone.
    </p>
    <p>
      Drivers, controls, and emergency modules may add small standby or auxiliary loads not included in
      light-engine wattage. For electrical panel sizing, consult an electrician with a fixture schedule.
      Heat output from LED fixtures is lower than legacy sources but still matters in tight plenum
      spaces — wattage correlates with heat dissipation at the luminaire.
    </p>
    <p>
      Use results to compare quotes (“Vendor A needs 120 W total at 90 lm/W vs Vendor B at 110 lm/W for
      the same lumen package”), estimate operating cost (watts × hours × energy rate), and sanity-check
      whether a product’s claimed lumens and watts imply realistic efficacy (values above ~200 lm/W for
      complete fixtures are uncommon; suspiciously low wattage for high lumen claims may indicate
      overstated marketing).
    </p>
    <Disclaimer />

    <h2>LED efficiency presets</h2>
    <p>
      These presets match common product tiers. Your actual project may mix efficacies if some areas use
      decorative or specialty fixtures.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Efficacy</th>
          <th>Typical use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {
          ledEfficiencyPresets.map((preset) => (
            <tr>
              <td>{preset.label.split(' — ')[0]}</td>
              <td>{preset.label.split(' — ')[1]}</td>
            </tr>
          ))
        }
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Example calculations</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>5,000 lumens at 100 lm/W:</strong> 5,000 ÷ 100 = 50 W — typical for a small home office
      zone after lux × area planning.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>10,000 lumens at 120 lm/W:</strong> 10,000 ÷ 120 ≈ 83 W — a common ballpark for a 20 m²
      office at 500 lux with efficient panels.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>25,000 lumens at 80 lm/W:</strong> 25,000 ÷ 80 ≈ 313 W — shows how poor efficacy increases
      power and heat for the same brightness target.
    </p>
    <p>
      Pair with the <a href="/color-temperature-guide">Color Temperature Guide</a> to choose LED CCT once
      wattage and lumen budgets are set.
    </p>
  </section>

  <FaqBlock faqs={lumensToWattsFaqs} />
  <RelatedTools currentHref={path} />
</ToolLayout>
